# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drupal-cms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] A **content management system** (**CMS**) is a computer software used to manage the creation and modification of digital content (content management).
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] It is typically used for enterprise content management (ECM) and web content management (WCM).
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] ECM typically supports multiple users in a collaborative environment, by integrating document management, digital asset management, and record retention.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Alternatively, WCM is the collaborative authoring for websites and may include text and embed graphics, photos, video, audio, maps, and program code that display content and interact with the user.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] There are two types of CMS installation: on-premises and cloud-based.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] On-premises installation means that the CMS software can be installed on the server.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Notable CMSs which can be installed on-premises are Drupal, Grav, Joomla, ModX, Wordpress.org and others.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] The cloud-based CMS is hosted in the vendor's cloud environment.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Publishing architectures vary significantly between systems.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Traditional coupled CMSs tie the content repository to a single presentation layer, suiting organisations publishing to one channel.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Headless CMSs separate the repository from presentation entirely, delivering content via APIs to websites, mobile applications, digital signage, or voice interfaces from a single source, an approach that has grown rapidly alongside the proliferation of digital touchpoints.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Authoring environments typically enforce structured workflows in which content passes through defined review and approval stages before publication, with role-based permissions controlling what each user can create, edit, or publish.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] The core CMS features are: indexing, search and retrieval, format management, revision control, and management.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Digital asset management systems are another type of CMS.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] They manage content with clearly defined author or ownership, such as documents, movies, pictures, phone numbers, and scientific data.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Companies also use CMSs to store, control, revise, and publish documentation.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] There are also component content management systems (CCMS), which are CMSs that manage content at a modular level rather than as pages or articles.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] CCMSs are often used in technical communication, where many publications reuse the same content.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Headless CMS, which separates content from its delivery layer, offers greater flexibility in content distribution across various platforms.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] According to W3Techs, the most widely used content management system is WordPress, used by 61.7% of websites as of March 2026.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Other commonly used content management systems include Shopify, Wix, and Squarespace .
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] If the cross-reference mechanism is well designed, the reader will be able to follow each cross-reference to the referenced content whether the content is presented in print or electronically.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] An author working in a content management system is responsible for identifying subjects of interest that cross documents, and creating appropriate systems of cross-references to support readers who seek to understand those subjects.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] For an individual cross-reference, an author should ensure that location and content of the target of the cross-reference are clearly identified, and the reader can easily determine how to follow the cross-reference in each medium in which publication is supported.
[src:drupal-cms/content-management-system] Content strategy practitioners (known as content strategists) specialize in planning content to meet business needs, taking into account the processes for creating and maintaining the content, and the systems that support the content.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The base of Drupal is known as **Drupal core**, which contains basic features common to content-management systems.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] These include user account registration and maintenance, menu management, RSS feeds, taxonomy, page layout customization, and system administration.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The Drupal core installation can serve as a simple website, a single or multi-user blog, an Internet forum, or a community website providing for user-generated content.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal also describes itself as a web application framework.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] When compared with notable frameworks, Drupal meets most of the generally accepted feature requirements for such web frameworks.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Although Drupal offers a sophisticated API for developers, basic Web-site installation and administration of the framework require no programming skills.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal runs on any computing platform that supports both a web server capable of running PHP and a database to store content and configuration.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In 2023/2024, Drupal received over 250,000 Euros from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal is officially recognized as a Digital Public Good.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal was originally written by Dries Buytaert as a message board for his friends to communicate in their dorms while working on his Master's degree at the University of Antwerp.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] After graduation, Buytaert moved the site to the public internet and named it Drop.org.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Between 2003 and 2008, Buytaert worked towards a PhD degree at Ghent University.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The name *Drupal* represents an English rendering of the Dutch word *druppel*, which means "drop" (as in a water droplet).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The name came from the now-defunct Drop.org, whose code slowly evolved into Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Buytaert wanted to call the site "dorp" (Dutch for "village") for its community aspects, but mistyped it when checking the domain name and thought the error sounded better.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal became an open source project in 2001.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Interest in Drupal got a significant boost in 2003 when it helped build "DeanSpace" for Howard Dean, one of the candidates in the U.S.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Democratic Party's primary campaign for the 2004 U.S. presidential election.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] DeanSpace used open-source sharing of Drupal to support a decentralized network of approximately 50 disparate, unofficial pro-Dean websites that allowed users to communicate directly with one another as well as with the campaign.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] By 2013, the Drupal website listed hundreds of vendors that offered Drupal-related services.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of 2014, Drupal is developed by a community.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] From July 2007 to June 2008, the Drupal.org site provided more than 1.4 million downloads of Drupal software, an increase of approximately 125% from the previous year.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of January 2017 more than 1,180,000 sites use Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] These include hundreds of well-known organizations, including corporations, media and publishing companies, governments, non-profits, schools, and individuals.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal has won several Packt Open Source CMS Awards and won the Webware 100 three times in a row.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 6 was released on 13 February 2008, on 5 March 2009, Buytaert announced a code freeze for Drupal 7 for 1 September 2009.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 7 was released on 5 January 2011, with release parties in several countries.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] After that, maintenance on Drupal 5 stopped, with only Drupal 7 and Drupal 6 maintained.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 7's end-of-life was scheduled for November 2021, but given the impact of COVID-19, and the continuing wide usage, the end of life was pushed back until 1 November 2023.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] This was extended once more as of June 2023 and was finally set for 5 January 2025.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 8 was first released on 19 November 2015.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] This was the first to use Symfony for components and Twig as a template engine and it also used the Composer for managing dependencies.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The last Drupal 8 was version 8.9.20 which was released on 17 December 2021.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 9 was released in 2020 and was created with easier upgrades and management in mind.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The first version was released on 3 June 2020 along with Drupal 8.9.0 with fewer major changes in project structure than in version 8.0, but with some of the old, deprecated code removed.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In October 2022, Drupal released an open source headless CMS accelerator, allowing the front end to be managed outside of the core system.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In April 2023, Drupal was recognized by the United Nations Digital Public Good Alliance as a digital public good.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In the Drupal community, "core" refers to the collaboratively built codebase that can be extended through contributory modules and—for versions prior to Drupal 8—is kept outside of the "sites" folder of a Drupal installation.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] (Starting with version 8, the core is kept in its own 'core' sub-directory.) Drupal core is the stock element of Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Common Drupal-specific libraries, as well as the bootstrap process, are defined as Drupal core; all other functionality is defined as Drupal modules including the system module itself.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In a Drupal website's default configuration, authors can contribute content as either registered or anonymous users (at the discretion of the administrator).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] This content is accessible to web visitors through a variety of selectable criteria.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of Drupal 8, Drupal has adopted some Symfony libraries into Drupal core.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Core modules also include a hierarchical taxonomy system, which lets developers categorize content or tag with keywords for easier access.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal core includes modules that can be enabled by the administrator to extend the functionality of the core website.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal includes core themes, which customize the "look and feel" of Drupal sites, for example, Garland and Bartik.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The Color Module, introduced in Drupal core 5.0, allows administrators to change the color scheme of certain themes via a browser interface.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] At DrupalCon Portland in 2024, Dries Buytaert called for the Drupal Community to create a new, modernized Drupal experience.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The project was initially called Starshot and it was an effort to reframe how people think of Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The project aims to deliver a more user-friendly and out-of-the-box version of Drupal, with a focus on ease of use, faster onboarding, and a polished default experience.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In 2025, this project was launched as Drupal CMS.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] This represents a shift toward making Drupal more accessible to non-developers while retaining its powerful, flexible core architecture.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal CMS includes a number of new artificial intelligence features.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] It also provides tools intended to support open-source, low-code and no-code development approaches.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of September 2022, Drupal is available in 100 languages including English (the default).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Support is included for right-to-left languages such as Arabic, Persian, and Hebrew.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal localization is built on top of gettext, the GNU internationalization and localization (i18n) library.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal can automatically notify the administrator about new versions of modules, themes, or the Drupal core.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] It's important to update quickly after security updates are released.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Before updating it is highly recommended to take backup of core, modules, theme, files and database.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] If there is any error shown after update or if the new update is not compatible with a module, then it can be quickly replaced by a backup.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] There are several backup modules available in Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] On 15 October 2014, an SQL injection vulnerability was announced and update was released.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Two weeks later the Drupal security team released an advisory explaining that everyone should act under the assumption that any site not updated within 7 hours of the announcement was compromised by automated attacks.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Thus, it can be extremely important to apply these updates quickly and usage of a tool like drush to make this process easier is highly recommended.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Prior to version 7, Drupal had functions that performed tasks related to databases, such as SQL query cleansing, multi-site table name prefixing, and generating proper SQL queries.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In particular, Drupal 6 introduced an abstraction layer that allowed programmers to create SQL queries without writing SQL.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 9 extends the data abstraction layer so that a programmer no longer needs to write SQL queries as text strings.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] It uses PHP Data Objects to abstract the database.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Microsoft has written a database driver for their SQL Server.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 7 supports the file-based SQLite database engine, which is part of the standard PHP distribution.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] With Drupal 9's new database abstraction layer, and ability to run on the Windows web server IIS, it is now easier for Windows developers to participate in the Drupal community.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] A group on Drupal.org is dedicated to Windows issues.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Since the release of Drupal 7, Web accessibility has been constantly improving in the Drupal community.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal is a framework dedicated for building sites accessible to people with disabilities because many of the best practices have been incorporated into Drupal Core.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 8 saw many improvements from the Authoring Tool Accessibility Guidelines (ATAG) 2.0 guidelines which support both an accessible authoring environment as well as support for authors to produce more accessible content.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The accessibility team is carrying on the work of identifying and resolving accessibility barriers and raising awareness within the community.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 8 has good semantic support for rich web applications through WAI-ARIA.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The community also added an accessibility gate for core issues in Drupal 8.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal core is modular, defining a system of hooks and callbacks, which are accessed internally via an API.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] This design allows third-party contributed modules and themes to extend or override Drupal's default behaviors without changing Drupal core's code.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal isolates core files from contributed modules and themes.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] This increases flexibility and security and allows administrators to cleanly upgrade to new releases without overwriting their site's customizations.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The Drupal community has the saying, "Never hack core," a strong recommendation that site developers not change core files.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Contributed modules offer such additional or alternate features as image galleries, custom content types and content listings, WYSIWYG editors, private messaging, third-party integration tools, integrating with BPM portals, and more.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of December 2019 the Drupal website lists more than 44,000 free modules.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of December 2019, there are more than 2,800 free community-contributed themes.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Themes adapt or replace a Drupal site's default look and feel.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal themes use standardized formats that may be generated by common third-party theme design engines.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Many are written in the PHPTemplate engine or, to a lesser extent, the XTemplate engine.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 8 and future versions of Drupal integrate the Twig templating engine.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The inclusion of the PHPTemplate and XTemplate engines in Drupal addressed user concerns about flexibility and complexity.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The Drupal theming system utilizes a template engine to further separate HTML/CSS from PHP.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] A popular Drupal contributed module called 'Devel' provides GUI information to developers and themers about the page build.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Community-contributed themes on the Drupal website are released under a free GPL license.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In the past, those wanting a fully customized installation of Drupal had to download a pre-tailored version separately from the official Drupal core.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Today, however, a distribution defines a packaged version of Drupal that upon installation, provides a website or application built for a specific purpose.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The distributions offer the benefit of a new Drupal site without having to manually seek out and install third-party contributed modules or adjust configuration settings.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] They are collections of modules, themes, and associated configuration settings that prepare Drupal for custom operation.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] For example, a distribution could configure Drupal as a "brochure" site rather than a news site or online store.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal is based on the Presentation Abstraction Control architecture, or PAC.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] It accepts input via a single source (HTTP GET and POST), routes requests to the appropriate helper functions, pulls data out of the Abstraction (nodes and, from Drupal 5 onwards, forms), and then pushes it through a filter to get a Presentation of it (the theme system).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] It even has multiple, parallel PAC agents in the form of blocks that push data out to a common canvas (page.tpl.php).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal.org has a large community of users and developers who provide active community support by coming up with new updates to help improve the functionality of Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] As of January 2017 more than 105,400 users are actively contributing.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The semiannual DrupalCon conference alternates between North America, Europe and Asia.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Attendance at DrupalCon grew from 500 at Szeged in August 2008, to over 3,700 people at Austin, Texas, in June 2014.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Smaller events, known as "Drupal Camps" or DrupalCamp, occur throughout the year all over the world.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The annual Florida DrupalCamp brings users together for Coding for a Cause that benefits a local nonprofit organization, as does the annual GLADCamp (Greater Los Angeles Drupal Camp) event, Coders with a Cause.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The Drupal community also organizes professional and semi-professional gatherings called meetups at numerous venues around the world.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] There are over 30 national communities around drupal.org offering language-specific support.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] By January 2023, The Drop Times became a Drupal-focused media outlet, highlighting stories of relevance to the Drupal community.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal's policy is to announce the nature of each security vulnerability once the fix is released.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Administrators of Drupal sites can be automatically notified of these new releases via the Update Status module (Drupal 6) or via the Update Manager (Drupal 7).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal maintains a security announcement mailing list, a history of all security advisories, a security team home page, and an RSS feed with the most recent security advisories.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In mid-October 2014, Drupal issued a "highly critical" security advisory regarding an SQL injection bug in Drupal 7, also known as Drupalgeddon.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Downloading and installing an upgrade to Drupal 7.32 fixes the vulnerability, but does not remove any backdoor installed by hackers if the site has already been compromised.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Attacks began soon after the vulnerability was announced.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] To solve the problem, the site must be restored using backups from before 15 October, be patched and manually updated, and anything merged from the site must be audited.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In late March 2018, a patch for vulnerability CVE-2018-7600, also dubbed *Drupalgeddon2*, was released.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The underlying bug allows remote attackers without special roles or permissions to take complete control of Drupal 6, 7, and 8 sites.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Drupal 6 reached end-of-life on 24 February 2016, and does not get official security updates (extended support is available from two paid Long Term Services Vendors).
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] Starting early April, large scale automated attacks against vulnerable sites were observed, and on 20 April, a high level of penetration of unpatched sites was reported.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] On 23 December 2019, Drupal patched an arbitrary file upload flaw.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] The file-upload flaw affects Drupal 8.8.x before 8.8.1 and 8.7.x before 8.7.11, and the vulnerability is listed as moderately critical by Drupal.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In September 2022, Drupal announced two security advisories for a severe vulnerability in Twig for users of Drupal 9.3 and 9.4.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] That week, Drupal also announced a patch for the S3 File System to fix an access bypass issue.
[src:drupal-cms/drupal] In January 2023, Drupal announced software updates to resolve four vulnerabilities in Drupal core and three plugins.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] A module interface expresses the elements that are provided and required by the module.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The elements defined in the interface are detectable by other modules.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The implementation contains the working code that corresponds to the elements declared in the interface.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modular programming, in the form of subsystems (particularly for I/O) and software libraries, dates to early software systems, where it was used for code reuse.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modular programming per se, with a goal of modularity, developed in the late 1960s and 1970s, as a larger-scale analog of the concept of structured programming (1960s).
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The term "modular programming" dates at least to the National Symposium on Modular Programming, organized at the Information and Systems Institute in July 1968 by Larry Constantine; other key concepts were information hiding (1972) and separation of concerns (SoC, 1974).
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modules were not included in the original specification for ALGOL 68 (1968), but were included as extensions in early implementations, ALGOL 68-R (1970) and ALGOL 68C (1970), and later formalized.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] One of the first languages designed from the start for modular programming was the short-lived Modula (1975), by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Another early modular language was Mesa (1970s), by Xerox PARC, and Wirth drew on Mesa as well as the original Modula in its successor, Modula-2 (1978), which influenced later languages, particularly through its successor, Modula-3 (1980s).
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modula's use of dot-qualified names, like `M.a` to refer to object `a` from module `M`, coincides with notation to access a field of a record (and similarly for attributes or methods of objects), and is now widespread, seen in C++, C#, Dart, Go, Java, OCaml, and Python, among others.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modular programming became widespread from the 1980s: the original Pascal language (1970) did not include modules, but later versions, notably UCSD Pascal (1978) and Turbo Pascal (1983) included them in the form of "units", as did the Pascal-influenced Ada (1980).
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The Extended Pascal ISO 10206:1990 standard kept closer to Modula2 in its modular support.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Standard ML (1984) has one of the most complete module systems, including functors (parameterized modules) to map between modules.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] In the 1980s and 1990s, modular programming was overshadowed by and often conflated with object-oriented programming, particularly due to the popularity of C++ and Java.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] For example, the C family of languages had support for objects and classes in C++ (originally C with Classes, 1980) and Objective-C (1983), only supporting modules 30 years or more later.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Java (1995) supports modules in the form of packages, though the primary unit of code organization is a class.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] However, Python (1991) prominently used both modules and objects from the start, using modules as the primary unit of code organization and "packages" as a larger-scale unit.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Perl 5 (1994) also includes support for both modules and objects, with a vast array of modules being available from CPAN (1993).
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] OCaml (1996) followed ML by supporting modules and functors.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modular programming is now widespread, and found in virtually all major languages developed since the 1990s.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The relative importance of modules varies between languages, and in class-based object-oriented languages there is still overlap and confusion with classes as a unit of organization and encapsulation, but these are both well-established as distinct concepts.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The term *assembly* (as in .NET languages like C#, F#, or Visual Basic) or *package* (as in Dart, Go, or Java) is sometimes used instead of *module*.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] In other implementations, these are distinct concepts; in Python a package is a set of modules, while in Java 9 the introduction of the Java Platform Module System, in which a new module concept, involving a set of packages with enhanced access control, was implemented.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] In Java, the term *package* is used for the module concept in the Java language specification.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The *module*, a kind of set of a package, was introduced in Java 9.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] In some Pascal dialects, the term *unit* is used for the module concept.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] A component is a similar concept, but typically refers to a higher level; a component is a piece of a whole system, while a module is a piece of an individual program.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] The scale of the term "module" varies significantly between languages; in Python it is very small-scale and each file is a module, while in Java 9 it is large-scale, where a module is a set of packages, which are in turn sets of files.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Conspicuous examples of languages that lack support for modules are C, and in their original forms, C++ and Pascal.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] C and C++ do, however, allow separate compilation and declarative interfaces to be specified using header files which is commonly considered modularization.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modules were added to Objective-C in iOS 7 (2013), and to C++ with C++20.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Pascal was superseded by Modula and Oberon, which included modules from the start, and various derivatives that included modules.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] JavaScript has had native modules since ECMAScript 2015.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] C++ modules have allowed backwards compatibility with headers (with "header units").
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Dialects of C allow for modules, for example Clang supports modules for the C language, though the syntax and semantics of Clang C modules differ from C++ modules.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Modular programming can be performed even where the programming language lacks explicit syntactic features to support named modules, like, for example, in C.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] This is done by using existing language features, together with, for example, coding conventions, programming idioms and the physical code structure.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] IBM i also uses modules when programming in the Integrated Language Environment (ILE).
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] With modular programming, concerns are separated such that modules perform logically discrete functions, interacting through well-defined interfaces.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Often modules form a directed acyclic graph (DAG); in this case a cyclic dependency between modules is seen as indicating that these should be a single module.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] In the case where modules do form a DAG they can be arranged as a hierarchy, where the lowest-level modules are independent, depending on no other modules, and higher-level modules depend on lower-level ones.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] A particular program or library is a top-level module of its own hierarchy, but can in turn be seen as a lower-level module of a higher-level program, library, or system.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] When creating a modular system, instead of creating a monolithic application (where the smallest component is the whole), several smaller modules are written separately so when they are composed together, they construct the executable application program.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Typically, these are also compiled separately, via separate compilation, and then linked by a linker.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] A just-in-time compiler may perform some of this construction "on-the-fly" at run time.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] These independent functions are commonly classified as either program control functions or specific task functions.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Program control functions are designed to work for one program.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Specific task functions are closely prepared to be applicable for various programs.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] This makes modular designed systems, if built correctly, far more reusable than a traditional monolithic design, since all (or many) of these modules may then be reused (without change) in other projects.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] This also facilitates the "breaking down" of projects into several smaller projects.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] Theoretically, a modularized software project will be more easily assembled by large teams, since no team members are creating the whole system, or even need to know about the system as a whole.
[src:drupal-cms/module-programming] They can focus just on the assigned smaller task.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Originally, taxonomy referred only to the classification of organisms on the basis of shared characteristics.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] It may refer to the classification of things or concepts, as well as to the principles underlying such work.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Thus a taxonomy can be used to organize species, documents, videos or anything else.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] A taxonomy organizes taxonomic units known as "taxa" (singular "taxon").
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] One function of a taxonomy is to help users more easily find what they are searching for.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] This may be effected in ways that include a library classification system and a search engine taxonomy.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Though often used interchangeably, taxonomies are distinct from typologies in that the former are concerned with empirical and objective characteristics, while the latter are concerned with abstract or subjective criteria.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The word was coined in 1813 by the Swiss botanist A.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] P. de Candolle and is irregularly compounded from the Greek τάξις, *taxis* 'order' and νόμος, *nomos* 'law', connected by the French form *-o-*; the regular form would be *taxinomy*, as used in the Greek reborrowing ταξινομία.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Wikipedia categories form a taxonomy, which can be extracted by automatic means.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] As of 2009, it has been shown that a manually-constructed taxonomy, such as that of computational lexicons like WordNet, can be used to improve and restructure the Wikipedia category taxonomy.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In a broader sense, taxonomy also applies to relationship schemes other than parent-child hierarchies, such as network structures.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Taxonomies may then include a single child with multi-parents, for example, "Car" might appear with both parents "Vehicle" and "Steel Mechanisms"; to some however, this merely means that 'car' is a part of several different taxonomies.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] A taxonomy might also simply be organization of kinds of things into groups, or an alphabetical list; here, however, the term vocabulary is more appropriate.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In current usage within knowledge management, taxonomies are considered narrower than ontologies since ontologies apply a larger variety of relation types.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Mathematically, a hierarchical taxonomy is a tree structure of classifications for a given set of objects.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] At the top of this structure is a single classification, the root node, that applies to all objects.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Nodes below this root are more specific classifications that apply to subsets of the total set of classified objects.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The progress of reasoning proceeds from the general to the more specific.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] By contrast, in the context of legal terminology, an open-ended contextual taxonomy is employed—a taxonomy holding only with respect to a specific context.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In scenarios taken from the legal domain, a formal account of the open-texture of legal terms is modeled, which suggests varying notions of the "core" and "penumbra" of the meanings of a concept.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The progress of reasoning proceeds from the specific to the more general.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Anthropologists have observed that taxonomies are generally embedded in local cultural and social systems, and serve various social functions.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Perhaps the most well-known and influential study of folk taxonomies is Émile Durkheim's *The Elementary Forms of Religious Life*.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Leibniz intended his *characteristica universalis* to be an "algebra" capable of expressing all conceptual thought.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Taxonomy in biology encompasses the description, identification, nomenclature, and classification of organisms.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Vegas et al. make a compelling case to advance the knowledge in the field of software engineering through the use of taxonomies.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Similarly, Ore et al. provide a systematic methodology to approach taxonomy building in software engineering related topics.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Several taxonomies have been proposed in software testing research to classify techniques, tools, concepts and artifacts.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Engström et al. suggest and evaluate the use of a taxonomy to bridge the communication between researchers and practitioners engaged in the area of software testing.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] They have also developed a web-based tool to facilitate and encourage the use of the taxonomy.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The tool and its source code are available for public use.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Websites with a well designed taxonomy or hierarchy are easily understood by users, due to the possibility of users developing a mental model of the site structure.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Frederick Suppe distinguished two senses of classification: a broad meaning, which he called "conceptual classification" and a narrow meaning, which he called "systematic classification".
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] About conceptual classification Suppe wrote: "Classification is intrinsic to the use of language, hence to most if not all communication.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Whenever we use nominative phrases we are classifying the designated subject as being importantly similar to other entities bearing the same designation; that is, we classify them together.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Similarly the use of predicative phrases classifies actions or properties as being of a particular kind.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] About systematic classification Suppe wrote: "A second, narrower sense of classification is the systematic classification involved in the design and utilization of taxonomic schemes such as the biological classification of animals and plants by genus and species.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Two of the predominant types of relationships in knowledge-representation systems are predication and the universally quantified conditional.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The "has-a" relationship is quite different: an elephant *has* a trunk; a trunk is a part, not a subtype of elephant.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The study of part-whole relationships is mereology.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Taxonomies are often represented as *is-a* hierarchies where each level is more specific than the level above it (in mathematical language is "a subset of" the level above).
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] For example, a basic biology taxonomy would have concepts such as *mammal*, which is a subset of *animal*, and *dogs* and *cats*, which are subsets of *mammal*.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] This kind of taxonomy is called an is-a model because the specific objects are considered as instances of a concept.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] For example, *Fido* is-an instance of the concept *dog* and *Fluffy* is-a *cat*.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In linguistics, is-a relations are called hyponymy.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] When one word describes a category, but another describe some subset of that category, the larger term is called a *hypernym* with respect to the smaller, and the smaller is called a "hyponym" with respect to the larger.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Such a hyponym, in turn, may have further subcategories for which it is a hypernym.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In the simple biology example, *dog* is a hypernym with respect to its subcategory *collie*, which in turn is a hypernym with respect to *Fido* which is one of its hyponyms.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Typically, however, *hypernym* is used to refer to subcategories rather than single individuals.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Researchers reported that large populations consistently develop highly similar category systems.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] This may be relevant to lexical aspects of large communication networks and cultures such as folksonomies and language or human communication, and sense-making in general.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Hull (1998) suggested "The fundamental elements of any classification are its theoretical commitments, basic units and the criteria for ordering these basic units into a classification".
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] There is a widespread opinion in knowledge organization and related fields that such classes corresponds to concepts.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] We can, for example, classify "waterfowls" into the classes "ducks", "geese", and "swans"; we can also say, however, that the concept "waterfowl" is a generic broader term in relation to the concepts "ducks", "geese", and "swans".
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] This example demonstrates the close relationship between classification theory and concept theory.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] A main opponent of concepts as units is Barry Smith.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Arp, Smith and Spear (2015) discuss ontologies and criticize the conceptualist understanding.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The book writes (7): “The code assigned to France, for example, is ISO 3166 – 2:FR and the code is assigned to France itself — to the country that is otherwise referred to as Frankreich or Ranska.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Smith's main argument - with which many followers of the concept theory agree - seems to be that classes cannot be determined by introspective methods, but must be based on scientific and scholarly research.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Whether units are called concepts or universals, the problem is to decide when a thing (say a "blackbird") should be considered a natural class.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] An important argument for considering concepts the basis of classification is that concepts are subject to change and that they change when scientific revolutions occur.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Our concepts of many birds, for example, have changed with recent development in DNA analysis and the influence of the cladistic paradigm - and have demanded new classifications.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Smith's example of *France* demands an explanation.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] First, *France* is not a general concept, but an individual concept.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Next, the legal definition of France is determined by the conventions that France has made with other countries.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] It is still a concept, however, as Leclercq (1978) demonstrates with the corresponding concept *Europe*.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Hull adds that in biological classification, evolution supplies the theoretical orientation.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Ereshefsky (2000) presented and discussed three general philosophical schools of classification: "essentialism, cluster analysis, and historical classification.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] These three categories may, however, be considered parts of broader philosophies.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Four main approaches to classification may be distinguished: (1) logical and rationalist approaches including "essentialism"; (2) empiricist approaches including cluster analysis.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] (It is important to notice that empiricism is not the same as empirical study, but a certain ideal of doing empirical studies.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] With the exception of the logical approaches they all are based on empirical studies, but are basing their studies on different philosophical principles).
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] (3) Historical and hermeneutical approaches including Ereshefsky's "historical classification" and (4) Pragmatic, functionalist and teleological approaches (not covered by Ereshefsky).
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In addition, there are combined approaches (e.g., the so-called evolutionary taxonomy", which mixes historical and empiricist principles).
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The historical and hermeneutical approaches is not restricted to the development of the object of classification (e.g., animal species) but is also concerned with the subject of classification (the classifiers) and their embeddedness in scientific traditions and other human cultures.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Natural classification is a concept closely related to the concept natural kind.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Stamos (2004) wrote: "The fact is, modern scientists classify atoms into elements based on proton number rather than anything else because it alone is the causally privileged factor [gold is atomic number 79 in the periodic table because it has 79 protons in its nucleus].
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Thus nature itself has supplied the causal monistic essentialism.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The periodic table is the classification of the chemical elements which is in particular associated with Dmitri Mendeleev (cf., History of the periodic table).
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] An authoritative work on this system is Scerri (2020).
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Hubert Feger (2001; numbered listing added) wrote about it: "A well-known, still used, and expanding classification is Mendeleev's Table of Elements.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Objectivity: The elements can be observed and classified by anybody familiar with the table of elements.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Completeness: All elements find a unique place in the system, and the system implies a list of all possible elements.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Simplicity: Only a small amount of information is used to establish the system and identify an object.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Predictions: The values of variables not used for classification can be predicted (number of electrons and atomic weight), as well as the existence of relations and of objects hitherto unobserved.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Bursten (2020) wrote, however "Hepler-Smith, a historian of chemistry, and I, a philosopher whose work often draws on chemistry, found common ground in a shared frustration with our disciplines’ emphases on the chemical elements as the stereotypical example of a natural kind.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Compounds, complexes, reaction pathways, substrates, solutions – these were the kinds of the chemistry laboratory, and rarely if ever did they slot neatly into taxonomies in the orderly manner of classification suggested by the Periodic Table of Elements.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Linnaean taxonomy is the particular form of biological classification (taxonomy) set up by Carl Linnaeus, as set forth in his Systema Naturae (1735) and subsequent works.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] A major discussion in the scientific literature is whether a system that was constructed before Charles Darwin's theory of evolution can still be fruitful and reflect the development of life.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Astronomy is a fine example on how Kuhn's (1962) theory of scientific revolutions (or paradigm shifts) influences classification.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Hornbostel–Sachs is a system of musical instrument classification devised by Erich Moritz von Hornbostel and Curt Sachs, and first published in 1914.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Each top category is subdivided and Hornbostel-Sachs is a very comprehensive classification of musical instruments with wide applications.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In Wikipedia, for example, all musical instruments are organized according to this classification.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In opposition to, for example, the astronomical and biological classifications presented above, the Hornbostel-Sachs classification seems very little influenced by research in musicology and organology.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] It is based on huge collections of musical instruments, but seems rather as a system imposed upon the universe of instruments than as a system with organic connections to scholarly theory.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] It may therefore be interpreted as a system based on logical division and rationalist philosophy.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) is a classification of mental disorders published by the American Psychiatric Association (APA).The first edition of the DSM was published in 1952, and the newest, fifth edition was published in 2013.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] In contrast to, for example, the periodic table and the Hornbostel-Sachs classification, its principles for classification have changed much during its history.
[src:drupal-cms/taxonomy-general] The first edition was influenced by psychodynamic theory.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A **web content management system** (**WCM** or **WCMS**) is a software content management system (CMS) specifically for web content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] It provides website authoring, collaboration, and administration tools that help users with little knowledge of web programming languages or markup languages create and manage website content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A WCMS provides the foundation for collaboration, providing users the ability to manage documents and output for multiple author editing and participation.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Most systems use a content repository or a database to store page content, metadata, and other information assets the system needs.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A presentation layer (template engine) displays the content to website visitors based on a set of templates, which are sometimes XSLT files.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Most systems use server side caching to improve performance.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] This works best when the WCMS is not changed often but visits happen frequently.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Administration is also typically done through browser-based interfaces, but some systems require the use of a fat client.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A web content management system controls a dynamic collection of web material, including HTML documents, images, and other forms of media.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A WCMS facilitates document control, auditing, editing, and timeline management.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] ) that users can apply to new and existing content, changing the appearance of all content from one central place.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Some WCMS systems support user groups, which control how registered users interact with the site.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A page on the site can be restricted to one or more groups.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] This means an anonymous user (someone not logged-on), or a logged on user who is not a member of the group a page is restricted to, is denied access.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] .is the ability to expand a single implementation (one installation on one server) across multiple domains, depending on the server's settings.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Once content is separated from the visual presentation of a site, it usually becomes much easier and quicker to edit and manipulate.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] editing tools allowing non-technical users to create and edit content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Most WCMS software includes plug-ins or modules that can be easily installed to extend an existing site's functionality.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Active WCMS software usually receives regular updates that include new feature sets and keep the system up to current web standards.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] management is the process of creating cycles of sequential and parallel tasks that must be accomplished in the WCMS.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] For example, one or many content creators can submit a story, but it is not published until the copy editor cleans it up and the editor-in-chief approves it.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] where many users retrieve and work on content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Changes can be tracked and authorized for publication or ignored reverting to old versions.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Other advanced forms of collaboration allow multiple users to modify (or comment) a page at the same time in a collaboration session.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Some WCMS software allows for various user groups to have limited privileges over specific content on the website, spreading out the responsibility of content management.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] from initial creation time, through revisions, publication, archive, and document destruction.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] WCMS software may provide a means of allowing each user to work within a virtual copy of the entire website, document set, and/or code base.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] This enables viewing changes to multiple interdependent resources in context before submission.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] They may also e-mail users when updates become available.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Many WCMSs can display content in multiple languages.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] , by which users check pages in and out of the WCMS.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Authorized editors can retrieve previous versions and work from a selected point.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] is useful for content that changes and requires updating, but it may be necessary to start from or reference a previous version.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A WCMS can use one of three approaches: *offline processing*, *online processing*, and *hybrid processing*.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] These terms describe the deployment pattern for the WCMS in terms of when it applies presentation templates to render web pages from structured content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] These systems, sometimes referred to as "static site generators", pre-process all content, applying templates before publication to generate web pages.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Since pre-processing systems do not require a server to apply the templates at request time, they may also exist purely as design-time tools.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] These systems apply templates on-demand.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] They may generate HTML when a user visits the page, or the user might receive pre-generated HTML from a web cache.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Most open source WCMSs support add-ons that extended the system's capabilities.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] These include features like forums, blogs, wikis, web stores, photo galleries, and contact management.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] These are variously called modules, nodes, widgets, add-ons, or extensions.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Some systems combine the offline and online approaches.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Some systems write out executable code (e.g., JSP, ASP, PHP, ColdFusion, or Perl pages) rather than just static HTML.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] That way, personnel don't have to deploy the WCMS itself on every web server.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Other hybrids operate in either an online or offline mode.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Others may be affordable based on size subscriptions.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Although subscriptions can be expensive, overall the cost of not having to hire full-time developers can lower the total costs.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] can be bought based on need for many WCMSs.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] A universal layout is created, making pages have a similar theme and design without much code.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] It makes it easy for beginner users to create custom front-ends.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] lets website content managers and other users update content without much training in coding or system maintenance.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] WCMSs provide the facility to control how content is published, when it is published, and who publishes it.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] management, guiding content managers through a series of steps required for each of their tasks.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Content freshness helps, as some search engines prefer websites with newer content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Social media plugins help build a community around content.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] RSS feeds automatically generated by blogs, or WCMS websites can increase the number of subscribers and readers to a site.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] URL rewriting can be implemented easily—clean URLs without parameters further help in SEO.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Some plugins specifically help with website SEO.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Larger scale implementations may require training, planning, and certifications.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Certain WCMSs may require hardware installation.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Commitment to the software is required on bigger investments.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Commitment to training, developing, and upkeep are costs incurred in any enterprise system.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Maintaining WCMSs may require license updates, upgrades, and hardware maintenance.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] files that reload every time data updates grow too large.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Because the URLs of many WCMSs are dynamically generated with internal parameters and reference information, they are often not stable enough for static pages and other web tools, particularly search engines, to rely on them.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] WCMS's are often forgotten about when hardware, software, and operating systems are patched for security threats.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] Due to lack of patching by the user, a hacker can use unpatched WCMS software to exploit vulnerabilities to enter an otherwise secure environment.
[src:drupal-cms/web-content-management-system] program to maintain the highest possible security standards.
